---
---

<section class="relative">
  <div class="container-page py-24 md:py-32 border-t border-[var(--color-hairline)]">
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-12 gap-10 lg:gap-16">
      <!-- Left: eyebrow + heading -->
      <div class="lg:col-span-5">
        <span class="eyebrow">What is this</span>
        <h2
          class="mt-3 text-[var(--color-ink)] text-balance font-semibold"
          style="font-size: clamp(2rem, 4.5vw, 3.25rem); line-height: 1.1; letter-spacing: -0.025em;"
        >
          21 markdown files your AI agent reads every session.
        </h2>
      </div>

      <!-- Right: prose + the surface list -->
      <div class="lg:col-span-7">
        <div class="space-y-5 text-[var(--color-ink-muted)] max-w-[55ch]" style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.6; letter-spacing: -0.005em;">
          <p>
            <code class="font-mono text-[0.94em] text-[var(--color-ink)] bg-[var(--color-surface-2)] px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded">@digitaloutbreak/workflow</code>
            is a scaffold — twenty-one files that get installed into your project.
            The files do three things: tell every AI agent how to read your project, give
            you slash commands for shipping work, and add a code-review subagent you can
            call when you need one.
          </p>
          <p>
            It is not a chatbot, not a daemon, not a runtime. The files just sit in your
            repo. The agent reads them every session, walks into every conversation
            already briefed on your stack, your conventions, and what you're working on.
          </p>
          <p>
            Install once with
            <code class="font-mono text-[0.94em] text-[var(--color-ink)] bg-[var(--color-surface-2)] px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded">npx skills add DigitalOutbreak/workflow -g</code>.
            Then in any project, run <code class="font-mono text-[0.94em] text-[var(--color-ink)] bg-[var(--color-surface-2)] px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded">/workflow-init</code>
            and answer a few questions. That's it.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
